sec.p:
So many public administration scholars have contributed in one way or another to this literature. John Halligan of the University of Canberra has done important work comparing reform initiatives and outcomes in OECD countries (e.g. Halligan, 2001a), and has compiled a progressive record of these initiatives and outcomes in the Commonwealth of Australia jurisdiction over a period of around 20 years (most recently Halligan, 2010). In more conceptual vein, Halligan (2001a: 1–15) has identified the main types of administrative reform as focusing on the following aspects of administrative life, many of which have strong NPM connections:


cutbacks and program review;



managerialization and marketization;



performance management;



accrual accounting and budgeting;



structure and organization;



decentralization;



privatization and corporatization;



competing for policy roles; and



external direction: the role of politicians and central agencies.
